Illinois lawmakers praise Syria diplomacy bid, but have deep doubts

The state's 20-member congressional delegation is sharply divided on whether
to give Obama use-of-force authorization to attack Syria.

     * [127]print

     *
     *

   By Katherine Skiba Tribune reporter

   7:02 a.m. CDT, September 11, 2013
   WASHINGTON -- Members of Illinois' congressional delegation voiced
   support Tuesday night for President Barack Obama's diplomatic efforts
   on Syria, but some expressed doubts that the regime of President Bashar
   Assad would cooperate and wariness over U.S. military strikes if it
   doesn't.

   In interviews and statements after Obama's prime-time address, Illinois
   lawmakers cited their constituents' concerns about military action and
   said it should be a "last resort."

   Illinois' 20-member congressional delegation is sharply divided on
   whether to give Obama authorization to attack Syria in retaliation for
   chemical attacks that the U.S. says killed more than 1,400 people last
   month. So far, only half the Illinoisans in Congress have declared
   where they stand or clearly indicated which direction they're leaning.
